  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Epitaph for the Lady of Tangseong, of the Hong Clan
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The late Lord of Yeonheung, the old master of Haengsan, had a grandson named Mun-bo. Through his guest from Seowon, Jeong Po, who had written down the deeds of the late lady, the grandson came weeping and spoke thus: "Our master was once bound in friendship with both our father and our uncle. Our mother's tomb cannot lack an inscription. Who but you could we ask to compose it?" I replied: "Alas, how could I refuse to offer my humble words?"

    The Hong clan of Tangseong is indeed a house of renown in our land. The grandfather, whose name was Ja-phan, served the Loyal and Fierce King as Grand Minister for fifteen years, holding the rank of Councilor. The father, named Gyeong, inherited his father's position and rose to the rank of Minister. The Lady was selected at thirteen to enter the Park household as a daughter-in-law, becoming the wife of the Esteemed Official and former Minister of Rites, Won, and was granted the title Lady of Tangseong. The eldest son, In-ryong, who has since passed, held the rank of Minister of Records. The second son, Mun-bo, became Vice Director of Ceremonial Rites. The third, Deok-ryong, was Deputy Commander of the Eastern Command. The fourth, Su-ryong, was General of the Celestial Guard. The fifth, Cheon-ryong, served as Inspector of Sureung. A daughter married Wang Ryeon and became Lady of Ikheung. Another daughter married into a scholarly family and became the wife of Heo Ryeong, an official.

    The Lady was born in the Mujae year of the Zhiyuan era. In the Byungja year of the Later Zhiyuan, at forty-nine years of age, she fell ill and passed away on the seventh month, Simyu day, her tomb consecrated on the eleventh month, Gapsu day.

    When she was laid to rest, In-ryong had already departed this world, and the Minister was attending at court and could not pay his final respects. Sorrowful indeed.

    Her epitaph reads:

    The Hong lineage of old,
    Its glory spreads through heaven's eastern realm.
    Not by mere accumulation,
    Nor by shallow virtue alone,
    Has this house grown so prosperous.

    In letters and in arms,
    Both virtue and merit shine.
    They labored to strengthen the realm,
    Each generation passing down loyalty.

    Granddaughter of the Grand Minister,
    This lady of surpassing grace—
    In youth she honored her parents,
    Most beloved among siblings.

    She chose her destined path,
    And entered the Park household.
        From the threshold onward,
    Her parents-in-law received her with joy.

    She perfected the arts of womanhood,
    Fulfilled the role of dutiful wife.
    She served her husband with propriety and counsel,
    Managed the household affairs with care,
    Leaving nothing incomplete or wanting.

    Many blessings came to pass—
    Two daughters and five sons.

    All spoke of the Lady:
    "Her years of blessing seemed endless."
    Yet fate proved otherwise.
    Her husband journeyed to distant halls,
    And she could not be there to greet his return.
    The path to the yellow springs stretches long and dim,
    Leaving endless sorrow in its wake.

    Alas, how grievous this is.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The work is an epitaph (墓誌) composed for the funeral stele of Lady Hong, wife of Park Won. Such epitaphs were important commemorative texts in East Asian funerary practices, intended to preserve the family's honor and the deceased's virtues for posterity.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem section (銘) follows classical Chinese epitaph conventions, using regulated verse to celebrate the deceased's lineage, virtue, and filial piety, while mourning her premature death.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the lady's husband 'attending at court' (赴輦下) suggests his official duties kept him from being present at her funeral—a detail that heightens the pathos of the work.
